
[1]sedulous

   SED'ULOUS, a. [L. sedulus, from the root of sedeo, to sit; as assiduous
   from assideo.] Literally, sitting close to an employment; hence,
   assiduous; diligent in application or pursuit; constant, steady and
   persevering in business or endeavors to effect an object; steadily
   industrious; as the sedulous bee.

   What signifies the sound of words in prayer, without the affection of
   heart, and a sedulous application of the proper means that may lead to
   such an end? L'Estrange.
